WEBVTT

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:09.280
What has been your biggest learning in creating all of this Shiny for Python magic?

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:12.320
Oh man, biggest learning. It's been so much.

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:16.879
A lot of different components involved in building this stuff. There's building Shiny

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:20.719
for Python itself, which was a really good learning experience. I hadn't really done

00:00:20.719 --> 00:00:27.040
a whole lot of Python programming before, but having the opportunity to implement Shiny again

00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:31.120
has been really interesting. It's given us a lot of chances to think about like,

00:00:31.120 --> 00:00:35.119
hey, do we really want to do things this way? Can we do things a better way?

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:40.480
With this web stuff, there's so much JavaScript programming and TypeScript programming,

00:00:41.279 --> 00:00:48.320
and just learning what the possibilities are here has been super fun. And it's been really

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:54.000
exciting to push the boundaries of what's possible. I feel like we're using stuff right

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:59.599
now that's sort of at the edge of what's possible. Like, hey, I want to build something.

00:00:59.599 --> 00:01:05.680
What I wish I had was a system that did this. And then being able to go and build that,

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:09.519
that's been really fun. I feel like it's juggling all the pieces,

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:14.559
like in making the transition from exploration to Shiny, like knowing when to stop exploring

00:01:14.559 --> 00:01:20.559
the data and to move it into a Shiny app. And also just how to get autocomplete for everything

00:01:20.559 --> 00:01:25.120
has been really helpful. A lot of people think about writing in VS Code, and you can do it like

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:29.599
in a notebook in VS Code too. But I think the reason notebooks are so useful is that oftentimes

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:35.839
I want to autocomplete like data too. And that's not like a static analysis. You can't just like

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:41.680
sit down with a script and autocomplete the columns of your data. So to me, it's been that

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:46.320
dance of like autocompleting the names of columns and stuff and being able to build an app.

00:01:46.959 --> 00:01:51.599
That's a really weird, actually, I think, uniquely data science space.

00:01:51.599 --> 00:01:56.559
It's hard to put yourself in the shoes of the users of something like this. If, you know,

00:01:56.559 --> 00:02:02.800
by definition, you are someone writing this app, you have experience and you're not, you know,

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:06.959
boots on the ground writing these apps every day. And so it's very easy to forget what's

00:02:06.959 --> 00:02:14.080
important and to prioritize the wrong things. The biggest, like long term learning thing has been

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:21.919
to not trust my immediate intuition about what is the most important thing to prioritize in

00:02:21.919 --> 00:02:28.240
development, because I'm probably wrong. As a data scientist, I still think that R is,

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:33.279
you know, is very much my tool of choice if I'm doing that kind of work where I'm like working

00:02:33.279 --> 00:02:39.440
with a new data set, trying to find interesting things from it. But coming to Python, and you know,

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:46.559
now my day job being more of a software engineer, where I'm the one responsible for

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:53.279
creating the software that data scientists will then use. It's been a really nice experience

00:02:53.279 --> 00:03:01.279
coming into Python and there being all of these kind of really mature, sophisticated libraries

00:03:01.279 --> 00:03:07.039
for building kind of the foundational piece of what you would need for a framework like Shiny.

00:03:07.039 --> 00:03:13.919
And not only that, but using VS Code with things like GitHub Copilot and just like the integrations

00:03:13.919 --> 00:03:21.839
with navigating large Python code bases in VS Code and all the like the extension ecosystem

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:32.240
and provides a really rich experience for navigating through large code bases and learning Python.

